In this update:
[1] USA: Texas case
[2] Prevention & false alarms

******
[1] USA: Texas case
Date: 5 Oct 2014
Source: Boston Globe [edited]
http://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2014/10/05/hospital-dallas-ebola-patient-critical/3zS3PgjSdovz5PmQKcW4oN/story.html


The hospital's explanation about what they knew about D's travel history has changed in the time since his diagnosis was revealed on Tue [30 Sep 2014].

Federal health officials have advised hospitals to take a travel history for patients with any Ebola-like symptoms. When D's diagnosis was 1st disclosed, the hospital said it wasn't until he came back Sun [28 Sep 2014] that they discovered he had been in West Africa. The hospital later acknowledged that D had told a nurse about his travel history on his 1st visit but said the information hadn't been fully communicated to the whole team.

On Thu [2 Oct 2014], the hospital elaborated by saying that a flaw in the electronic health records systems led to separate physician and nursing workflows and that the doctor hadn't had access to D's travel history.

But the hospital issued a statement late Fri [3 Oct 2014] saying that the doctor who initially treated D did have access to his travel history after all. Hospital spokesman Wendell Watson said on Sat 4 Oct 2014 that he could provide no further details, saying: "We're still looking into the entire chain of events."

[But did the doctor see the names Liberia and/or West Africa? The transcript excerpt released by the hospital stated simply: "Africa," which would have raised malaria as the most likely diagnosis; see ProMED-mail post "Ebola virus disease - ex Africa (04): USA ex Liberia, prevention," archive No. 20141004.2832236. - Mod.JW]
