[2] Prevention & false alarms

Canada: Toronto hospital patient negative for Ebola
-----------------------------------------------
[4 Oct 2014]: (Global News Canada) "The result is negative, which means that the Ebola isolation protocol is discontinued," said Gillian Howard, VP of public affairs for the University Health Network, in a statement released late Friday night [3 Oct 2014].
http://globalnews.ca/news/1598325/toronto-hospital-patient-kept-in-isolation-tests-negative-for-ebola

--
USA: Patients monitored for possible Ebola symptoms
-----------------------------------------------
5 Oct 2014: (WFLA) 2nd Florida patient with Ebola-like symptoms cleared...
http://www.wfla.com/story/26709355/a-second-florida-patient-with-ebola-like-symptoms-has-been-cleared

--
USA: Vomiting man removed from flight in Newark is Ebola-free
-----------------------------------------------
4 Oct 2014: (Bloomberg) A sick passenger was pulled off a flight arriving at New Jersey's Newark Liberty International Airport [New York] from Brussels [Belgium]. The man, who vomited on the plane, doesn't have the virus, according to state health officials. Still, passengers on United Airlines flight 998 were kept in their seats for almost 2 hours as quarantine officers from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention removed the ill individual and a daughter traveling with him.
http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-10-04/vomiting-man-removed-from-flight-in-newark-on-ebola-fear.html

[The Liberian in a Dallas hospital with EVD also arrived in the USA via Brussels, so the index of suspicion is high, although we are not told the country of origin of this person. - Mod.JW]

--
USA: Ebola ruled out in 2 suspected cases in Washington DC region
-----------------------------------------------
4 Oct 2014: (Baltimore Sun) Howard University Hospital in Washington DC quarantined a patient Fri [3 Oct 2014] who had recently traveled to Nigeria out of "an abundance of caution," officials said. On Sat [4 Oct 2014], officials said the hospital, in conjunction with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, had determined the patient did not have Ebola. Shady Grove Adventist Hospital in Rockville [Maryland, USA] also determined late Fri [3 Oct 2014] that their patient had malaria, not Ebola. The unidentified patient was isolated after arriving with suspicious symptoms and travel history. Ebola, malaria and cholera have similar symptoms early on, including fever and vomiting... Maryland is one of 13 states capable of testing for Ebola, in tandem with the CDC and with its authorization...
http://baltimoresun.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81586866

--
USA: more than 100 possible cases across the US, all false alarms
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The CDC has been scrambling to check more than 100 possible reported cases across the US over the last week, all of which have proved false alarms. Dr Frieden said: "We're seeing more people calling us, considering the possibility of Ebola. That's what we want to see. We don't want people not to be diagnosed."...- more
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/ebola/11142123/British-American-Ebola-patient-due-to-arrive-in-US.html

--
USA: screening in West Africa & on arrival
---------------------------------------------------------
5 Oct 2014: (Daily Mail UK) Federal officials have said every passenger travelling from all countries ravaged by the infection could face the checks such as having their temperature taken on arrival. A source told CNN that 'all options are on the table' but says the increase in measures would not be as easy as it sounds as most routes from West Africa are not direct. They said: 'There aren't that many direct flights from Ebola-affected countries to the U.S. anymore. Many passengers are arriving on connecting flights from other parts of the world, and then they come here, so that makes it more of a challenge.' [CDC Director] Friedan stood by the screening procedures, pointing out today that 77 people have been prevented from getting on planes in West Africa thanks to the efforts of airport officials who were trained by the CDC.

http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2781703/Americans-set-face-increased-screening-airports-amid-Ebola-crisis-CDC-FINALLY-considers-giving-passenger-arriving-Liberia-medical-check-arrival.html#ixzz3FK7vzG2l

